paragraphs.title: Running a notebook
paragraphs.text:
%md
## Notebook Overview

Notebooks help you tell a story about your data using a combination of text formatting and computer programming languages (referred to as *interpreters*) using any number of paragraphs (cells). A paragraph is a unit of code or text that you can execute to produce code results, built-in visualizers, charting library renderings and more. Paragraphs might also simply use the *Markdown* language to present nicely formatted descriptive text, this paragraph being an example.

The blue *Run* button in the upper left of the notebook can be used to run all of the paragraphs in the notebook in order. Alternatively you can click on the small arrow play button at the upper right of any paragraph to run that paragraph alone. Next to the play button are a few other icons allowing you to show and hide the code and results sections of the paragraph as well as a gear menu containing a number of other functions to do things such as move the paragraph up or down, show and hide the title and delete the paragraph.

In addition to running the notebook manually it can also be set to run at regular intervals using the scheduler found in the "..." menu to perhaps update insights being mined from dynamically updated data sources. Streaming data comes to mind here such as that from IoT sensors and stock prices.

Notebooks are displayed with the *Default* look and feel view mode but can also be switched to a *Report* mode to better format the content for non-technical stakeholders by hiding any code blocks. Another mode called *Juno* emulates the formatting of a Jupyter notebook to help Jupyter users make the transition to Zepl. These view modes are available from the text link just to the left of the *Settings* link at the top right of the notebook.

Note that there are keyboard shortcuts for most of the functions of the paragraph listed in the "..." menu at the top right of the notebook. This makes it easy to do things like run the paragraph and perform other functions without moving the mouse away from the code you're writing.

paragraphs.title: Multiple Interpreters
paragraphs.text:
%md
Each paragraph in a single notebook can run a different interpreter.

Interpretpers are identified by a "%" sign and the name as the first statement of the paragraph. This notebook has Python set as the default so we don't need to specify it.

Here is the current set of available interpreters:

* `%python`: [Python2 or Python3]

    * `%python.sql`: Pandas sql. Query Pandas dataframes with SQL
    * `%python.conda`: Manage Conda environments and install additional Python packages

* `%spark`, `%pyspark`: [Apache Spark 2.1]
    * `%spark.sql`: Spark SQL. Query Spark dataframes with SQL
    * `%spark.dep`: Load additional Scala and Java libraries
* `%md`: Markdown
* `%athena`: AWS Athena
* `%jdbc`: SQL database

paragraphs.title: System Sources
paragraphs.text:
%md
Zepl provides a convenient way to connect with many popular data sources such as Snowflake and S3 via an object interface that can be created once and used by all.

**Data Sources** specify various criteria about the data such as database, schema, bucket and so on depending on the source. Once created, data sources can be attached to notebooks for easy data access. They also provide credential keychain management removing the need to expose secrets in your code.

**Uploaded Files** allow you to access data directly from files uploaded from your local file system.

Both methodologies allow you to access the data via Python and other languages.

paragraphs.title: Built-in Visualizers
paragraphs.text:
%md
Built-in visualizers make it quick and easy to start exploring your data without having to write any code. They are made available either by writing SQL queries or by using an internal *z* object's *show* method. Zepl provides a basic tabular view by default with a number of other options such as bar, pie, radar and sankey charts. These charts can be customized to show and pivot on the data at hand as well as change axis labels and color schemes.

The neighboring paragraph visualizes the Pandas data frame created above using a bar chart with a dynamic form generated by using special syntax that generates a variable allowing us to filter the query. We can choose which data to visualize using the *Show Settings* button as well as set the various parameters of the graph via the *Parameters* section.

paragraphs.text:
%md
Any third party JavaScript charting library can be utilized via Zepl's HTML rendering capability. Here we present two examples of interactive graphs running in the notebook via HTML code printed from Python; the first is an animated chart using *Plotly* and then second is a drill-down chart using *HighCharts*.

import numpy as np
import matplotlib.mlab as mlab
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

np.random.seed(0)

# example data
mu = 100  # mean of distribution
sigma = 15  # standard deviation of distribution
x = mu + sigma * np.random.randn(437)

num_bins = 50

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(20, 12))

# the histogram of the data
n, bins, patches = ax.hist(x, num_bins, density=1)

# add a 'best fit' line
y = mlab.normpdf(bins, mu, sigma)
ax.plot(bins, y, '--')
ax.set_xlabel('Smarts')
ax.set_ylabel('Probability density')
ax.set_title(r'Histogram of IQ: $\mu=100$, $\sigma=15$')

# Tweak spacing to prevent clipping of ylabel
fig.tight_layout()
plt.show()

%python
import matplotlib
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np
from mpl_toolkits.mplot3d.axes3d import Axes3D

alpha = 0.7
phi_ext = 2 * np.pi * 0.5

def flux_qubit_potential(phi_m, phi_p):
    return 2 + alpha - 2 * np.cos(phi_p) * np.cos(phi_m) - alpha * np.cos(phi_ext - 2*phi_p)

phi_m = np.linspace(0, 2*np.pi, 100)
phi_p = np.linspace(0, 2*np.pi, 100)
X,Y = np.meshgrid(phi_p, phi_m)
Z = flux_qubit_potential(X, Y).T

fig = plt.figure(figsize=(30,10))

# `ax` is a 3D-aware axis instance because of the projection='3d' keyword argument to add_subplot
ax = fig.add_subplot(1, 2, 1, projection='3d')

p = ax.plot_surface(X, Y, Z, rstride=4, cstride=4, linewidth=0)

# surface_plot with color grading and color bar
ax = fig.add_subplot(1, 2, 2, projection='3d')
p = ax.plot_surface(X, Y, Z, rstride=1, cstride=1, cmap=matplotlib.cm.coolwarm, linewidth=0, antialiased=False)
cb = fig.colorbar(p, shrink=0.5)
